name: James Taylor
answer: James Taylor (born July 22, 1953, New York City, New York, USA) is best known as lead guitarist of The James Gang, a late 1960s-1970s power rock trio from Niles, Ohio. The band originally consisted of Taylor, drummer and singer Jim Bonfanti and bassist-keyboardist and singer Joe Walsh. Formed in 1966, The James Gang released five albums between 1969 and 1971 and several singles, all of which, except for "Funk #49" (#59, 1970) were unsuccessful commercially. Taylor left the James Gang in 1971 to become an ordained Episcopal priest in Evanston, Illinois. During his tenure at St. Paul's Episcopal Church, in Evanston, Illinois, Taylor worked in the food pantry and at Chicago's Marillac Social Services Center. He remained at the parish until 1995, then became an English teacher at Harper Woods High School in Harper Woods, Michigan. Taylor is currently (2011) serving as Rector of the Assumption Church in Windsor, Ontario. When he is not working at the church, he is at the band Coolpix Studios.

answer: Shayne Neumann (born 25 July 1970) is an Australian politician who was the Australian Labor Party member for Dickson in the House of Representatives from the 2010 federal election until his defeat in the 2013 election. name: Gonzalo Fonseca
answer: Gonzalo Fonseca (20 February 1922 – 12 April 1997) was an Uruguayan sculptor best known for his large-scale fountain and mural projects executed in Europe, the United States and Venezuela. A native of Montevideo, Fonseca studied at the Academie Julien, Académie de la Grande Chaumière and from 1948 to 1958 was a pupil of Ossip Zadkine in Paris who had a lasting influence on his work. He was a friend of the Surrealist artist Yves Tanguy. In 1959, Fonseca returned to his native Uruguay for the first time and began to work in a studio outside Montevideo provided by the Tacuarembó Department government. In 1961, he became the second artist after David Smith to build open-air works in welded metal at the Chase Manhattan Plaza in New York City. He later built his fountain at the Chase Manhattan Plaza by way of a work grant from the National Endowment for the Arts. In 1968 he had a retrospective at the Whitney Museum of American Art, New York, and was commissioned in 1966 for a sculpture for the atrium of the new Museum Building in the Pan-American Life on 375 Stuyvesant Street in New York, New York, and had built his retrospective exhibition began in 1971. name: Michael Valpy
answer: Michael Valpy (August 20, 1945) is an influential Canadian newspaper and broadcasting journalist. He was appointed to the Senate of Canada on October 6, 2016 on the advice of Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and sat as an independent until his mandatory retirement on August 20, 2019, due to his age. He was educated at Trinity College School and the University of Western Ontario, where he received a Bachelor of Arts degree, and the University of Toronto's graduate journalism program, where he completed a master's degree in 1968. He worked in a number of capacities, including reporter, parliamentary correspondent, Washington correspondent, Toronto bureau chief, managing editor of the Globe and Mail Atlantic bureau.

name: Toyoko Tokiwa
answer: Toyoko Tokiwa (Tokiwa Toyoko 常磐豊子;1915 – 2009) was a Japanese woman who was wrongfully convicted of murder. In 1949, she was working in a hospital in Kobe when a patient named Umeko Okubo was found to be ill and, after some treatment, later died. As a condition of her employment, Tokiwa was required to stay in the hospital at night and provide services for the patients, and she did this at the time of Okubo’s death. However, Tokiwa soon became a suspect (along with Hana Tokiwa, who had been a patient in the hospital at the time of Okubo’s death) after the police decided that the cause of death was a heart attack, with cyanide poisoning a probable cause. Tokiwa’s lawyer’s attempts to convince the jury by pointing out some scientific flaws in the investigation, though unsuccessful in the district court and the Tokyo Court of Appeal, finally led to an acquittal in May 1951.

name: Daniel Charles
answer: Daniel Charles (September 5, 1868 – April 17, 1954) was an American sportsman and yachtsman. He was born in New York City to John Charles of New York City and the former Mary C. Stevens.[2] In 1909, he married Florence Osborne Hutton, the former wife of William C. Hutton and daughter of George L. Osborne.[3] Charles was the co-owner of a yacht, the Rainbow. In 1914, Charles was a co-owner of Rainbow II, the winner of the International 12 Metre Class sailboat championship races. On July 25, 1914, his son-in-law, Richard W. Deering, was lost at sea in a motor boat accident on the Bay of Fundy. On the night of May 12, 1915, Charles and a party of five friends were trapped on a yacht when a severe thunderstorm rolled off the sea. An attempt to return with the use of the motor failed and the party was swept off the boat into the sea. The party was found unconscious but safe the next morning and all were taken to a hospital. Charles died on April 17, 1954 at St. Joseph's General Hospital at Brooklyn, New York.

name: Gilberto Silva
answer: Gilberto Silva (born 7 April 1976) is a retired Brazilian footballer who played as a defensive midfielder for Arsenal. He made 154 appearances for Arsenal from 2002 to 2008, scoring 3 goals. He represented the Brazil national team 39 times from 2002 to 2005, scoring 2 goals and being named in the Brazilian 2002 FIFA World Cup squad. He started his career at América Mineiro before signing for French club AS Monaco in 1999. A year later, he transferred to Arsenal for £4 million. He stayed for six seasons, winning three FA Cup winners medals (in 2002, 2003 and 2005), one FA Premier League winners medal (in 2004) and being part of the 'Invincibles team' (who remained unbeaten in the 2004 FA Premier League and were a 38 game unbeaten team). Gilberto Silva was a member of Arsenal's unbeaten 2003–04 Premier League winning team. He currently lives in England where he still lives with his family. Gilberto retired on 20 May 2008. He also holds the record for the most World Series Games Played with four, and the record for Putouts with 2416.

name: António de Oliveira Salazar
answer: António de Oliveira Salazar (April 29, 1889 – July 27, 1970) was a Portuguese economist and professor who was Prime Minister of Portugal from 1932 to 1968, with a hiatus from 1951 to 1958, when there was a dictatorial corporatist regime (see Estado Novo); he was also ruler of Portugal's colonial empire from 1932 until late 1968, after which Portugal was left with its integrated overseas provinces of Portuguese East Africa, Portuguese Timor and the colonies of São Tome and Principe. During his 28-year dictatorship he was given the nickname by opponents the Iron Salazar. In spite of being a devout Catholic, Salazar was fascinated by the idea of the corporate state as a means of national rejuvenation for Portugal and a bulwark against Communism. On July 12, 1968, Salazar suffered a cerebral vascular accident, which forced him to retire, though he was able to recover his health and the ability to write. He would die two years later.

answer: Annika Sörenstam (pronounced [²sœːrəns(t)am]; born 9 October 1970) is a Swedish professional golfer whose accomplishments in the sport have made her the most successful female golfer in history. name: Robert Smith, Baron Smith of Kelvin
answer: Robert Smith, Baron Smith of Kelvin (born 17 February 1942) is a British engineer and cross bench member of the House of Lords, who held the office of Lord Mayor of London from 2009 to 2010. He is founder and former chairman of energy and environmental consultancy group Amec Foster Wheeler. Smith studied engineering and business administration at the University of Strathclyde and Massachusetts Institute of Technology before working for Royal Dutch Shell, including posts in the United Kingdom, Netherlands and South Africa. He joined Bain and Company in the 1970s, and became head of the international management consultancy KPMG. Smith became chairman of BT Group in 2001 (later non-executive director) and chairman of the British government-privatised Weapons Research Establishment at Fort Halstead in Kent.

name: Errol Flynn
answer: Errol Flynn (20 June 1909 - 14 October 1959) was an Australian-born actor who achieved fame as a Hollywood actor in the 1930s and 1940s. name: Ramesses IV
answer: Ramesses IV (or Ramesses the Great or Ramesses the Great and Good; Ancient Egyptian rꜥ-ms-sw /rˤed-msw/ "Ra-power is strong") was the third pharaoh of the Twentieth Dynasty, Ramesses' great-grandson. His only known act was to cut a window on the south wall of the sanctuary at Karnak Temple, so that transfers of the sacred bark or barks of Amun of Karnak might be more easily accomplished. Since his only wife was the king's own daughter, and he only had one daughter, he and his wife only spent two years on the throne after becoming king. The king only ruled for a year—it is possible that his death was not natural, and that he was killed in connection with a harem coup at the highest levels of Egypt's royalty. name: Paul Kruger
answer: Paul Kruger (October 10, 1825 – July 14, 1904) was one of the leading figures in 19th century South Africa, and the last President of the independent Transvaal Republic. He gained international renown as the face of the Boer cause that led to the Second Boer War. He was known as "The Lion of Pretoria," and later as "Khamajena" (meaning "The old man with the long grey beard") by his countrymen. As president of the Republic of Transvaal, he tried to resist intrusions by the British, such as the influx of Uitlanders (Afrikaans and English for "foreigners") into the region. This resulted in the Second Boer War. Kruger's forces went to war with the British Army by first invading the Cape Colony in 1899, just before the Second Boer War, a conflict in which Kruger was personally present. After the war Kruger left Cape Colony and moved out of South Africa. After the Boers had left the Cape Colony, the South African Republic was split. One half of this republic was the Transvaal and the other half was the Orange Free State. The state of South Africa consisted of the provinces of the Transvaal and Orange Free State.
